Bring 350ml of water to the boil with 1/4 tsp of @salt{1/4%tsp}. Pour in the
@bulgur wheat{3/4%cup}, place a #pot{} on the #stove{} and rest off the heat for
~{25%minutes}, or until the water has completely soaked into the bulgur wheat.

== Mint Raita ==

In the meantime, you can prepare everything else. First off, the mint raita.
Finely chop the @mint{5}(finely chopped) and combine with the @Greek style natural
yoghurt{5%tbsp}, 1/4 tsp of salt and a pinch of @black pepper{pinch} in a small
#bowl{}. Pop in your #fridge{} for later.

== Tabbouleh ==

Now it's time for the tabbouleh. Chop the @vine tomatoes{2}(chopped) into
roughly ½cm pieces and finely chop the @spring onion{3}(finely chopped) and
@flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped), add them to a large bowl. Juice half the
@lemon{1/2} and add this too, together with 3 tbsp of @olive oil{3%tbsp}, 1/4 tsp
of salt and 1/4 tsp of black pepper. Set aside until the bulgur wheat is ready.

== Moroccan Spiced Halloumi ==

Finally, the halloumi! Cut the @halloumi{1} into eight even slices. In a bowl,
mix 1 tbsp of @olive oil{1%tbsp} with the @harissa spice mix{1/4%tsp}.

> Tip: Add less harissa if you want the halloumi less spicy.

Mix in the halloumi and make sure all sides are coated well. Heat a #frying pan{}
on medium-high heat, and once hot add in the halloumi without adding extra oil.
Fry the halloumi for ~{2-3%minutes} on each side, until slightly charred.

The bulgur wheat should now be ready. Strain any excess water and pop into the
bowl with the rest of the tabbouleh ingredients, mix well.

Serve the halloumi on top of the tabbouleh and dress with the mint raita.
Enjoy!